Title: Visualizing Bayesian Inference in the Beta-Binomial Model
Date: 2019-03-13
Tags: Bayesian Statistics, R, Data Visualization
Slug: beta-binomial
Status: published
Authors: Will Hopper
Summary: The leap from "discrete" Bayes to "continuous" Bayes is always tricky. If you've struggled to make the connection, maybe it's because no one has every shown you the joint probability distribution that makes up the numerator of Bayes rule. We'll visualize that joint distribution in this post, and simplify things by treating this joint distribution like a familiar contingency table to reveal the machinery of Bayesian inference about real-valued model parameters.
JavaScripts: jquery.min.js, bootstrap.min.js, html5shiv.min.js, htmlwidgets.js, plotly.js, typedarray.min.js, crosstalk.min.js, plotly-latest.min.js
Stylesheets: crosstalk.css, plotly-htmlwidgets.css

Bayesian Inference - for something that begins with such a simple and elegant mathematical rule, it gets complicated fast. This is especially true when you first take the leap from "Discrete Bayes" (where all the random variables you're working with represent a small set of mutually exclusive events) to "Continuous Bayes" (where the random variables and parameters you're working with are real-valued numbers). Even if you have a good intuition behind what Bayes rule does and good algebra skills, it's challenging to transfer what you've learned in the discrete setting to this new continuous landscape.

In this post, I'm going to try and bridge this gap by highlighting the similarity between joint probability distributions involving continuous random variables, and contingency tables involving categorical random variables, and using this similarity to perform Bayesian inference about a probability parameter.

### Contingency Tables
Most people are introduced to joint and conditional probability through the vehicle of contingency tables, which show the relationship between the frequencies or probabilities of two categorical variables. For example, here's a contingency table showing the relationship between breast cancer and biological sex probabilities (based on rates from [the National Breast Cancer Foundation](https://www.nationalbreastcancer.org/breast-cancer-facts) and this [Scientific American Article](https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/is-a-pregnant-womans-chan/)).

<h5 id=table_1>Table 1: Joint distribution of biological sex at birth and breast cancer development</h5>

|                      | Male   | Female   | Total  |
| -----                | ------ |  ------  |  ----- |
| **Breast Cancer**    | .00512 |  .061    |  .0612 |
| **No Breast Cancer** | .50688 |  .427    |  .9338 |
| **Total**            | .512   |  .488    |        |

A few things to note about this table:

1. The 4 middle cells are *joint probabilities*, which tell us the probability of both events occurring. For example, this table tells us the probability of being born female **and** developing breast cancer is around .061 (6.1%). All 4 of these values sum up to one.
2. The values in the rows and columns titled "Total" are *marginal probabilities*, which tell us the probability of a single event happening. They get this name because they can be calculated by summing all the values in a single row/column (and then writing the value in the margin of that row/column). Both sets of marginal distributions sum up to one.

I like contingency tables because they give us a simple visual method for finding *conditional probabilities*, which are the probability of one event occurring **given another event has occurred**. An example of this would be the probability of developing breast cancer **given** that a person was born female. In other words, if we already know a person was born female, what is the probability they will go on to develop breast cancer?

With a contingency table, we can answer this question very easily. We simply:

1. Find the the row or column of the event that we know has already happened - in this case, the column for "Female".
2. Find the cell in this column which corresponds to the combination of female, and the outcome whose probability we're interested in - in this case, the cell for "Female" & "Breast Cancer".
3. Take the value in this cell (the joint probability) and divide it by the **total** probability of the event we have observed (being born female).
4. That's it! In this case, the probability of developing breast cancer **given** that a person was born female equals .061/.488 = .125, which is one-eighth.

## Bayes Rule, Discretely
This example is all fine and good, but what does it have to do with Bayesian Inference? Well, constructing a contingency table is my favorite way to solve problems that require applying Bayes rule, because Bayes rule is all about finding a conditional probability. I think this approach is a good way to turn a problem that involves some weird, tricky formula, into a plain old "find a conditional probability" problem.

As a reminder, Bayes rule is given by the following equation:

$$
p(B \vert A) = \frac{p(A \vert B)p(B)}{p(A)} = \frac{p(A \cup B)}{p(A)}
$$

where the right-most fraction is another version of the middle fraction (the numerator is just changed according to the definition of joint probability, $p(A \cup B) = p(A|B)p(B)$).

To give an example of a problem that might ask you to employ Bayes Rule, consider the following:
I ask you "What is the probability the patient is a man, given a diagnosis of breast cancer?

To help you answer this, I might tell you the overall probability of being born a man, and overall probability of developing breast cancer (i.e., the marginal probabilities), and also tell you the conditional probability of being female given a diagnosis of breast cancer is .9967. This starts us off with the following (empty) contingency table:

|                      | Male   | Female   | Total  |
| -----                | ------ |  ------  |  ----- |
| **Breast Cancer**    |        |          |  .0612 |
| **No Breast Cancer** |        |          |  .9338 |
| **Total**            | .512   |    .488  |        |

We can use the definition of joint probability, $p(A \cup B) = p(A|B)p(B)$, to compute the probability of being born female and developing breast cancer by multiplying the conditional probability of being female given a diagnosis of breast cancer (.9967) by the overall (i.e., marginal) probability of developing breast cancer (.0612), which gives the same value we had previously, .061.

|                      | Male   | Female   | Total  |
| --                   |   -    |  ----    |   -    |
| **Breast Cancer**    |        |    $p(A \cup B) = p(A \vert B)p(B) = \\\\ .9967 \times .0612 = .061$    |  .0612 |
| **No Breast Cancer** |        |          |  .9338 |
| **Total**            | .512   |    .488  |        |

With this cell in place, we can use the fact that each row and column must sum to it's marginal probability to complete the last 3 cells in the contingency table. Now, we can answer to the question at hand: What is the probability the patient is a man, given a diagnosis of breast cancer?

We'll employ the same technique as before, when we found the probability of developing breast cancer given that a person was born female. This time, we divide the joint probability of being born male and developing breast cancer (.00512, see [Table 1](#table_1)) by the overall probability of being born male (.512) to get our answer: .01, or 1/1000. Neat!

## Continuous Bayes
But a 2x2 contingency table is hardly the only situation Bayes rule can be applied to. In reality, we might acknowledge some uncertainty in the "true" probability of developing breast cancer. We might *estimate* it to be .0612 in a longitudinal study, but this one study might under or over-estimate it. The true probability might be a little higher, like .07, or a bit lower, like .05. There's even some small chance the study was done completely wrong, and the true probability might be .2, or .3!

In many situations where we want to estimate some unknown quantity, like a probability, it makes sense to put a probability distribution over all possible values of this quantity. In Bayesian statistics, this is called the prior distribution. We had a prior all along in this example - it was the base rate of developing breast cancer. But in the previous example, our prior wasn't much of a distribution; it was just a single value. Now what we want to do is use a function that describes the likelihood of **all** possible probabilities, all the way from 0 to 1.

One probability distribution that fits the bill is the [Beta distribution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beta_distribution), graphed below:
![Beta_distribution](https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f3/Beta_distribution_pdf.svg/500px-Beta_distribution_pdf.svg.png)

It has 2 parameters, $a$ and $b$. If $a$ and $b$ have similar values, then the beta distribution is roughly symmetrical (thought it can even be convex *or* concave!). As $a$ and $b$ diverge, the distribution gets more and more skewed.

To illustrate Bayesian inference in this context, let's imagine we're aliens from the planet Bayes who have just landed on Earth, and have been given a job immediately - estimate the probability of developing breast cancer. But, since we're aliens, people aren't eager to sign up for our "medical study" - just 10 people agree. We're going to come up with our estimate of this probability, which we will denote with the symbol $\theta$, by following these 10 people for 5 years and seeing how many develop breast cancer.

Since we're aliens from the planet Bayes, we've decided to employ Bayesian inference in our estimate of this probability $\theta$. But since we have no prior knowledge of earthly diseases, we use a prior distribution for the probability of developing breast cancer that is pretty vague, and centered on .5 (a 50/50 chance). We decide to use a $Beta(\alpha=5, \beta=5)$ distribution, shown below:

![beta_5_5]({filename}/img/beta_5_5.png)

And since we're looking at the discrete "Yes, Developed breast cancer" or "No, didn't develop breast cancer" outcomes for 10 people, we know that the probability of each possible outcome (0 developed, 1 developed, 2 developed, etc.) follows a [binomial distribution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binomial_distribution). We'll denote the number of people who develop breast cancer with the symbol $x$

So, at this point we have the two numerator components of Bayes Rule in place - the prior, and the likelihood. To make this mapping explicit:
$$
p(\theta) = Beta(\alpha=5, \beta=5) \\\\
p(x\vert\theta) = Binomial(N=10, p=\theta)
$$

The last thing we need is the denominator $p(x)$, the probability of observing $x$ cases of breast cancer out of 10 people. This value is found by solving the integral of $\int_{0}^{1}p(x\vert\theta)p(\theta)d\theta$, but I don't think that's a good way to illustrating the machinery of Bayesian inference in this case.

To paint a clearer picture, let's instead treat the product of the Binomial likelihood and the Beta prior likelihood (which forms the numerator of Bayes Rule in this case) as a huge contingency table. We'll do this by discretizing the Beta distribution at 100 different values of $\theta$, using each of these as an input to our Binomial distribution likelihood, and weighting the resulting likelihoods of 0 to 10 people developing breast cancer by the likelihood of that particular value of $\theta$ from our Beta distribution.

Below is some R code to implement the process of forming this 11 by 100 contingency table - the key part is inside the `for` loop, where we calculate and weight the Binomial likelihood using each individual value of `p`.

```r
p <- seq(0, 1, .01) # Grid of probabilities
# Empty matrix to fill in with likelihoods
y <- matrix(NaN, nrow=11, ncol=length(p),
            dimnames = list("Succeses"=as.character(0:10),
                            "Probaability" = as.character(p))
            )
# Probability of 0-10 successes for each value of p,
# weighted by that p's prior likelihood
for (i in 1:length(p)) {
  y[,i] <- dbinom(0:10, p[i], size=10) * dbeta(p[i], 5, 5)
}
```

The last thing we're going to do with this contingency table is *normalize* it - right now, it's not a table of probabilities, it's a table of likelihoods (which is a [different thing](https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/31238/what-is-the-reason-that-a-likelihood-function-is-not-a-pdf)!). To convert it into probabilities (which sum to 1) we'll divide each value in the table by the total area under the surface formed by the values in the table. We can compute this by summing up all the values in the table, but conceptually we know this value is going to be 100, because we have 100 Binomial distributions which each sum to 1.

```r
# Divide by area to normalize into probabilities
y <- y/sum(y)
```
Let's visualize this probability contingency table. I've plotted it down below in an interactive [plotly](https://plot.ly/d3-js-for-r-and-shiny-charts/) chart, so grab your mouse and take this figure for a literal spin.

Each point along this surface is a joint probability - the probability of a specific value of $\theta$ being the true probability of developing breast cancer (assuming our $Beta(5, 5)$ prior distribution) **and** of observing a specific number of breast cancer cases out of 10 people. The probability is highest where the number of cases and the true probability are similar (i.e., a .5 probability, and 5 cases occurred). Each of the colored lines traces out a "defective" Binomial distribution that shows the probability us a specific probability parameter from our Beta prior. and each of the smooth black curves represents a defective Beta distribution.

Now, let's assume that in our study of these 10 people, 3 developed breast cancer over the next 5 years. How does this data affect our estimate of the probability of developing breast cancer?

We'll use the same technique we used with out 2x2 contingency tables. First, we'll find the row/column representing the event we want to "condition on", which is the "3 out of 10" column in this case. Then, we sum this entire column to find the marginal probability, which is the overall probability of observing 3 cases of breast cancer out of 10. Lastly, we'll take the value in the cell we're interested in, and divide by the sum of all the probabilities in this column (the marginal probabilities). Only this time, there's not just one cell we're interested in, there are 100 - because we had a prior *distribution* of potential probabilities. So, we divide all 100 cells by this marginal probability to form our **posterior distribution**, the $p(\theta|x)$.

```r
# posterior given 3 successes, 7 failures
my_posterior <- y[4,]/sum(y[4,]) # it's the 4th row because 0 cases is in row 1
```

To help understand this process, imagine taking each the values intersecting the grey hyperplane (which represents observing 3 cases out of 10), and dividing it by the sum of all the values intersecting the grey hyperplane.

Here's what that posterior distribution looks like compared to our prior distribution:
![beta_5_5]({filename}/img/beta_posterior_8_12.png)

We can see that our posterior is narrower, and centered on a value around .4, instead of .5. So, our experiment has made us more certain that the true probability of developing breast cancer is less than .5, and is most likely around .4.

To make sure our contingency table style of analysis has given us the right answer, we can compared the mean of **our** posterior distribution with [the analytic solution](https://ldabook.com/parameter-estimation.html#bayesian-inference), which actually calculates the marginal probability using integration. The precise posterior in this case (assuming a Beta(5, 5) prior, a binomial likelihood where 3 cases were observed out of 10 trials) is a $Beta(5 + 3, 5 + 7) = Beta(8, 12)$ distribution. Since we know the mean of a Beta distribution is $\frac{a}{a + b}$, we know the mean of our posterior should be $\frac{8}{8 + 12} = .4$.

Let's check our work by finding the expected value of our posterior "table". Remember, the expected value of a variable $x$ equals $\sum_{n=1}^{n} x_{i}p(x_{i})$. Here, our variable is $\theta$ (called `p` in our code), and the values in our posterior give the probability of each value of $\theta$.
```r
sum(my_posterior*p)
```

```
## [1] 0.4
```
Excellent! We did it right! Our "table-derived" point-estimate for the probability of developing breast cancer matches that of the analytic solution. But we as aliens need to collect a lot more data - an estimate of .4 isn't going to win us the trust of many earthlings.

## Wrap-up
So, what did we learn? We learned that Bayesian inference about a value described using a continuous probability density function isn't a different beast at all. It's still all about turning a joint probability into a conditional probability by dividing by a marginal (i.e., total) probability. It's just more complicated to calculate the individual parts because we have to work with functions instead of just single values.

Instead of multiplying .061 and .996 to compute the joint probability, we would have to multiply a Binomial distribution and a beta distribution. And in order to compute the marginal probability of observing breast cancer, we'd have to compute an integral instead of summing a column. But, that's only because integrals are the continuous analog of discrete summation! It's the same old Bayes rule, with the same old steps, but just with more advanced mathematical machinery used to compute each part.
